segments.text: This is an interview with Ms. Rocio Powell by Carrie Weber on April 12, 1976, for an oral history project in Geography 311.
We came to Texas in 19 and 29 from Tennessee.
My husband worked for the railroad.
We came knowing the opportunities would be better here.
We lived in Kaufman, TX about 18 months.
We came to Groves back.
And live there two years.
We came to her and in 34 her and was slow for progress a while.
We had two schools, elementary and high World War Two came on.
I had two boys to go in the Navy.
They were in the invasion on Guana Canal and Imajima.
We were gone.
They were gone three years.
Come home safe.
We have a new post office now.
Used to have one on the old building on the corner of 4th.
We have.
very few side, we had very few sidewalks.
What we had were brick.
We had a cotton mill, an oil mill, which are gone now.
Very few people had cars.
They were Model Ts, and now most everybody has a nice car.
Our school system has improved so much.
The children would go, would come to school at 8 o'clock, get out at 4,
They that lived any distance would bring their lunch.
We had no hospitals, had one doctor named Alexander.
He died years ago.
After the war, Dr. Searcy and Dr. Fleming built a little hospital.
Dr. Searcy died, Dr. Boyd and Dr. Gwines built the big hospital which we have now, and we are very proud.
We lived
On Market Street, we had a bench in the corner of our yard.
A&M boys would come and sit on that bench waiting for a ride.
That was in 1940, 42, and 43.
I have seen A&M go into a university.
Someday, A&M will be the biggest college anywhere.
I sent my grandson, John Pastor, to A&M, which graduated in 75 and is now in law school.
I am an A&M fan.
I can go back to when you were in Tennessee.
You taught school there, right?
Well, I taught school in Tennessee.
I went to college in Murfreesboro, Tennessee.
And it was strictly a teacher's college.
And I majored in English and Home Ec.
And today, it's like A&M.
Any field you want to get into to go to teacher's college, why, you can get into it, for it covers all
I have one of my friends sent me a picture of it last year and it's a big college now.
But when I went there and then I taught school about six months.
And then I quit and then we we came to Texas and but I never did teach school here, but I always belong to the PTA.
And I have had children in school ever since 19 and 20.
And this year, Karen will graduate from high school here.
And I won't have nobody else in school.
Of course, I guess she'll go to college somewhere, which John wants her to go to A&M.
I don't know where she'll go.
Did you come from a large family?
Me?
No.
I had one brother.

and one sister and my brother's dead i am the only one that's living in my family and i'm 84 years old your husband was with the railroad right and my husband died in 1970 and all his family is gone in fact my children is about all i've got in the relation in the relative part and uh
No, they're all gone.
All my children, I have five girls and three boys, and they're all living.
Well, what was the main industry in Hearn?
What was the main industry in Hearn when you all got here?
Cotton, railroading, cotton mill and oil mill.
Was it wells?
I mean, for the oil.
Was it wells or what?
No, the oil.
See, they had the cotton mill.
They'd take the cotton seed and stuff and make oil.
And it's all closed up now.
And then we had the Humboldt and the Texaco people, you know these tanks you see out here?
Well, they used to have gasoline and oil in them, and now there's nothing.
When did they come in?
Oh, honey, I just don't know when they did, because they're here when I come here.
But they've been closed for.
Oh, I guess 25 years.
That's one reason that Hearn is not.
We don't have the best school system in the world, and that's why we don't have any money.
You know, it's got a town has got to be prosperous for money to pay teachers and we have to have what you call the.
Where they can't get a job nowhere else because they don't have the money to pay them.
But we've got no income.
But nothing to bring their money in.
Nothing where taxes would be.
Now railroading.
I've seen the day when they would be a whole block when they'd get their checks going to the bank.
Now there's 15 or 20 going.
And of course that brought a resource in for schools.

and uh as well as a hern has never let nothing come in here and they didn't couldn't realize what they're cutting their nose off to spite the face by not doing it and you know that the factory over in brian that i believe is baker shoe factories well they wanted here and the city manager wouldn't let them come here and they went over there and they built
When they went there, they just had one little place there on the corner.
Well, now they have a whole, you know how much, how big it is.
That's why Brian, I have seen Brian grow.
They used to, between Brian and College Station, that was all woods.
And you see where he is now, don't you?
Because that's why Brian is worth so much.
And it's prospered because they have let stuff come in.
They have built and hung just a town that won't build or won't let business come in.
They're not going to get nowhere.
That's true.
And that's the way it is here.
They just never would let nothing go here.
Used to, I can remember A&M how it used to be.

that we used to have trains to run through we'd ride on you know the agriculture part was over on this side and the mechanical part was over on that side is the old building still over there the agriculture part i'm not sure which one are you referring to i imagine it is i haven't been on that side and i don't know when but every that's the way it used to be

that and now who has grown and still are growing even now john of course finished in three years at a m because he went all the time and in that three years how it has how a m has built and still a building in growing and i remember when uh they let girls start oh they had a woog

they didn't and the boys didn't want the girls to come and a lot of the people didn't say it was boys college and let's keep it that way but i never could understand why they didn't want it because the girls had the same right to go that the boys did and now why you know where it is with them they have a well i think that uh
I think our school system is better all the way around than it used to be, but it used to be we didn't have nothing to do nothing with.
That was one thing.
And then another thing, used to nobody, the majority of children that went to school, their parents had money.
And now, if you want an education, money's not the object.
Because there'll be some way for you to go.
If you want an education now, it's up to you.
Because you can get the means to go on.
Do you think Hearn needs more education, I mean a better education system, more schools?

think what you think is her not to improve their schools well they would if they could but they can't they've got nothing to do nothing with it takes money takes money to do things our teachers here well i don't know hardly how they live but of course this is not a such a this is just a country town life because they don't make much
But then they're glad we've got a very few teachers that has two degrees.
Well, you know now most any school, any town, well, they're going to require that teacher to have two degrees anyhow.
Well, we have teachers here that don't even have a degree that substitute teachers.
Well, a lot of the parents kick about it.
But what you going to do?
They haven't got money to hire teachers with to hire extra teachers.
They're sub teachers.
We have a girl.
She's got five children.
And she's going to A&M now.
And she substitutes here sometimes.
She hasn't been to A&M a year.
And some of the parents are just kicking the wall out about it.
You know, don't want her

to teach said she wasn't qualified well she just teaches the low grades she uh one out of high school could teach a low grade child in the first grade or kindergarten or something well i've just been ripped down the back because i said we can't get nobody else and i said let her teach and let her keep on going to a m and

no we our school system is not the best and that's why it's money we don't have income to pay teachers you know you got to have uh you take brian every way you turn around now there's something that makes that is taxed to make money for the schools for a certain part of all of it goes to the school
It's just like with paying anything else.
We only have one highway patrolman here.
Of course, he is paid by the county, but the city has to pay him so much, too.
But they don't have no money.
Poor, poor pay.
We can get a good policeman here, come in here, and next thing you know, he's either gone to Byron or to Houston or Temple or somewhere.
More money?
Because they just don't have their money to do with.
It takes money to do most anything that's where you're going to accomplish something.
You're going to have to have money.
It's going to have to come from somewhere.
But let it be honest, we're losing a bank here now.
We've had lots of trouble with it.
I don't know.
Well, do you think that Hearn did better when they had the cotton mills around?
Oh, sure.
Anytime with anything, you take like the railroad.
My husband was yard foreman.
And up until about
He retired in 65.
And up until about 60, he worked from 18 to 20 men.
And when he quit, he had to retire on account of his health.
And then he was working 8 of 10, and now they work 4.
And you see all of that.
They moved off to different places.
Some of them, when they'd get cut off, they were younger men.
They'd go somewhere else where they could get on.
Well, the next day he'd work three, and maybe this man would have eight or nine children.
Well, a lot of times I would fix up a big pan of meal, great big pieces of meat and dried beans and send out
To that family.
To what you had to.
You didn't want him to cry for something to eat.
And as to us, we had plenty to eat, a good house to live in, a car to drive and everything like that.
But the man that was a working.
Why it made it hard on him because he helped somebody else.
Especially if like we wash daddy worked there with me and.
And you become attached to the crew that you're working.
And we just, of course, some of them, they had some men that were single.
Well, there's all right what they drew.
But you take a man, and especially way back then, it seemed like that the black especially, we had one man that had 11 children.
And I couldn't see those children cry for hunger.
And, of course, that made it hard then on me.
And, of course, now people won't call it a depression.
But I don't know what else harder that we are in.
People, of course, I do think, though, that people, that times is getting a little bit better.
It seems like there's more work for people than there was.
For I know about two years ago.
There wasn't work for nobody and everything high.
Well, I think.
That if we can ever get the government straightened out.
Why I think times will get better.
And I think it's up to the people.
You know this sitting back and saying now.
I don't know why in the world that we don't get a so-and-so, a good governor, a good president, a good so-and-so in Congress, or do this or do that.
We'll have to get up and do something about it.
I don't know.
They don't do it, though.
That's true.
Do you remember what the wages were like?
What kind of wages the railroad was paying back then?
Oh, my gracious.
In 1930, in Grovesburg, people worked for 50 cents a day.
Not on the railroad.
I think the railroad men made about, of course, daddy was on salary.
But then, I believe then his salary was $150 a month.
But you could take $10 and go to the grocery store and buy enough groceries to last a month.
And when he quit, he was making close to $1,000 a month.
Now, that's the way it had to come up.
But you could get a job today of making $20 a day.
And you could work five days at $20.
You go to buy something, they know what you're making.
As salary and wages go up, stuff's going to go up.
So they're going to get your money.
That's just the way the ball bounces.
It's always been that way, more or less.
Especially in recent years, it's been more so.
We had...
I had my children far apart, but last I had four girls, and the grown ones called them the little girls, and my baby will be 45 years old in September.
I used to go to town, and I'd buy them pair of shoes for $1.98.
They were shoes, too, like you buy now and give $18, $20 for it.
Well, then the dollar was worth more in those days, though, wasn't it?
Karen bought her pair of shoes in Lubbock.
They got a sole on them and a strap and gave $20 for them.
Well, did you ever have a job other than teaching?
What?
Did you ever have a job other than teaching?
No.
I was in college when I married.
And I kept house.
My baby boy graduated from Sam Houston.
And one day they were talking in class.
And this professor asked the children what their parents did.
And they come to Jack and said, Jack, does your mother work?
He said, my mother's got the most important job there is in the world.

jacks he he was deciding he said that some of them turned around and looked he said what does your mother do he said she is a wife and my mother well if you think about it to be a mother it's not everybody that has a baby is a mother i know plenty of people that
They've got three or four children, but they're getting short.
With being like this should be.
And if you are a mother of Christian mother and raise children and educator.
Why you've helped the world, you've helped.
The progress of time for that boy girl.
Maybe.
All right, you take it this way.
My baby boy.
Has three degrees.
He has BS degree in master.
From Sam Houston and then he has PH degree which he got.
He went to about five different colleges.
And he.
Is over special in education for delinquent boys and girls and retardation.
He places retarded children in.
Two homes where their parents can't take care of him properly.
He has a good job.
Well, since he has so much, I mean, has some experience in teaching, do you think that the educational process, I mean, how they teach children has changed much?
Oh, mercy, yes, and much better.
But let's take the retaliation.
Used to, if anybody had a retarded child, that child was kept at home.

and a lot of people didn't ever even see that child because so many parents i guess they felt embarrassed that's my notion but now retarded children has a chance now just like with jack he goes into homes these children are in our schools here we have a teacher that teaches retarded children
And used to, I know one, especially I have a friend that has a girl retarded.
Well, she started that child to school.
She's as old as Karen.
And, of course, you can tell she's retarded all right enough.
But a long time ago, when that child started to school, she couldn't have talk.
She didn't know anything.
Her mother had never taught her nothing.
And now she can read and write, and she's a nice-looking girl.
Now, and she goes to church regularly.
You don't ever see her talking to anybody.
I don't walk up to her and I say, Mel Ballou, how are you doing?
Fine.
Oh, yes, education has improved.
Wonderful.
Wonderful.
Y'all ever had any racial problems you heard?
Oh, yes.
When they first started to integrate here, some of the whites, and after it done been law and everything, they wasn't going to let them go.
And of course, I always belonged to the PTA.
And when this day school started, used to mothers would go.
Well, John was in the sixth grade.
And that morning when we got to school, they'd hired a colored teacher.
Oh, here comes some of them because I was the oldest mother or grandmother.
We're not going to have her.
Our children, we're going to do this and we're going to do that.
I said, let me tell you something right now.
You're up against a brick wall.
I said, we sat in the saddle.
We didn't think it would come.
I didn't.
They didn't.
And I said, it's come, and you better go home and keep your mouth shut.
Well, I'm going to teach my child that first thing she says, pick up a rock and hit her.
I said, you are headed for trouble.
When I got home, I said, John, you sit down.
We're going to have a little roundtable discussion.
He sat down.
I said...
Ms. Robinson was her name, and she's crazy about John now.
I said, you say yes ma'am and no ma'am to her, and if ever any trouble, you come and tell me, I'll settle it.
Wasn't no time till John was crazy about her, and she's crazy about John.
But oh, she had it rough for a while.
They fought, the black and the white fought,
They'd done everything you could think of doing, but John never was in it.
He had better not ever been in it either.
We had it.
We didn't have to have it.
But people said, oh, that won't ever come.
The black and white won't ever mix.
Well, after it was passed, what are you going to do?
There was nothing you could do.
And she was a good teacher.
Is she still teaching?
No, she retired.
She has a nice brick home over here.
Oh my goodness, I can see her.
She'll see Karen.
She wants to know how John is.
